  "presentation_notes": {
    "opening": "I respect the instinct to build. You get full control, no vendor dependency. But let's look at the real numbers.",
    "tco_walkthrough": "[Point to table] Initial development: $300K to $500K‚Äî4 to 6 engineers for 3 to 6 months. Infrastructure: $50K to $100K per year. Ongoing maintenance: $200K to $400K per year‚Äî2 to 4 engineers full-time. Feature development: $100K to $200K per year for new connectors and features. Monitoring and operations: $50K to $100K per year for on-call and incident response. [Point to total] Total 3-year TCO for DIY: $1.5M to $3.3M. With Expanso: $360K to $900K‚Äîthat's 25% of the savings we deliver. Difference: You save an additional $1.1M to $2.4M by buying versus building.",
    "qualitative": "[Point to bottom section] Beyond the money: Time to value‚Äî6 to 12 months for DIY versus 2 to 4 weeks for us. Risk‚Äîhigh for DIY, zero for us because of the free pilot. Opportunity cost‚Äîyour engineers stay focused on product, not infrastructure. Scalability‚Äîwe're proven at scale with 50+ customers. Innovation‚Äîautomatic updates versus having to build every feature yourself. [Acknowledge] The one advantage of DIY: Full control, no vendor dependency. That's real. You have to decide if that's worth $1M+ more.",
    "common_objection": "If they say 'But we have cheap engineering resources offshore': That's a tempting calculation. But: (1) Hidden costs‚Äîcoordination, quality, rework. (2) Opportunity cost‚Äîthose engineers could build revenue-generating features. (3) Risk‚Äîprojects often take 2-3x longer than estimated. (4) Ongoing burden‚Äîthis isn't build once, it's continuous investment.",
    "when_to_use": "Use this slide when prospect says 'We're considering building this ourselves' or 'We have engineering capacity'"
  },
  "use_case": "Build vs buy discussions, engineering-led organizations, cost-conscious buyers"
